div.p: Prisma is not like Convex or MongoDB Atlas in the “cloud-hosted storage” sense — it’s more of a database toolkit/ORM than a database provider.
Here’s the breakdown:

li.p: An ORM (Object–Relational Mapper) and type-safe database client for Node.js and TypeScript.
It doesn’t store your data; instead, it connects to your database (PostgreSQL, MySQL, MongoDB, SQLite, etc.) — wherever that database is hosted.
You run Prisma in your backend code (server, serverless function, etc.), and it queries your database directly.
Prisma itself does not host or deploy your backend — you deploy your backend code wherever you want (Vercel, Netlify, AWS Lambda, etc.).

div.class: _tableWrapper_1rjym_13 group flex w-fit flex-col-reverse

tr.td: Wherever your DB is (local, AWS RDS, Neon, Supabase, etc.)

div.class: sticky end-(--thread-content-margin) h-0 self-end select-none
absolute end-0 flex items-end

button.class: hover:bg-token-bg-tertiary text-token-text-secondary my-1 rounded-sm p-1 transition-opacity group-[:not(:hover):not(:focus-within)]:pointer-events-none group-[:not(:hover):not(:focus-within)]:opacity-0

li.p: Neon = PostgreSQL database hosting (cloud)
Prisma = the TypeScript client + migration tool your backend uses to talk to Neon

hr.p: If you use Convex:

li.p: Convex stores your data and runs your backend logic — you don’t need a separate DB.

div.p: Exactly ✅ — Prisma is basically:
A smart toolkit + client library that:

li.p: Knows your database schema (via your schema.prisma file).
Generates type-safe queries automatically so you don’t manually write raw SQL.
Connects to any hosted database (Neon, Supabase, RDS, Atlas, PlanetScale, local Postgres/MySQL, etc.).
Handles migrations — keeps your database schema in sync with your code.

hr.p: 💡 Think of it like this:

li.p: Without Prisma → you write SQL manually and use a basic database driver.
With Prisma → you just call prisma.user.findMany() and Prisma turns that into optimized SQL for your specific database.

hr.p: So Prisma itself is not your DB, and it’s not your backend — it’s the bridge between your backend code and your database (which could be cloud-hosted or local).
If you want, I can show you a small before-and-after example of querying with and without Prisma so you can see how much it abstracts.

div.p: Not exactly — Neon isn’t a full BaaS like Convex.
Here’s the difference:

li.p: BaaS (Backend-as-a-Service) — you write functions, deploy them, and Convex runs + scales the backend for you.
Handles database + API layer + auth + storage in one package.
You don’t need a separate server — Convex is your backend.
Cloud-hosted Postgres provider — it’s just the database (but very nice Postgres).
Similar to MongoDB Atlas, Supabase’s Postgres, or AWS RDS.
No API or backend code hosting — you need your own backend (Node.js, Next.js, etc.) or use an ORM like Prisma to connect to it.

hr.p: 💡 In short:

li.p: Convex = Backend + Database + API in one.
Neon = Just the database (PostgreSQL) hosted in the cloud.

hr.p:
If you’re using Prisma + Neon → Prisma is your query toolkit, Neon is your DB.
If you’re using Convex → Convex already includes query functions and backend hosting, so you wouldn’t need Prisma or Neon.
If you want, I can make a comparison table of Convex vs Neon vs Prisma so the roles are super clear.

div.p: This error usually happens when you try to manipulate DOM elements (like removing a child) before the DOM is ready or when the element you want to remove doesn’t exist.
Given the code you shared with conditional rendering in Next.js, the most likely cause is:

li.p: Using usePathname() outside a client component (it requires a client component).
Or manipulating DOM manually somewhere that runs before the element exists.

hr.h3: How to fix this error in your case:

li.p: Ensure your RootLayout has "use client" at the top since usePathname() is a client-only hook.
Check if you have any manual DOM manipulation like removeChild in your code or libraries you use. If yes, make sure it runs only after the component is mounted (inside useEffect).

div.p: This error means you are trying to use the useSession hook (or some Clerk hook) outside of the <ClerkProvider> context. Clerk requires that any hooks like useSession, currentUser(), or components like <SignIn /> must be rendered inside the <ClerkProvider>.

hr.p: In Next.js 13 app directory, you should wrap your entire app inside <ClerkProvider> in your root layout or root provider component.
Example in app/layout.tsx (or app/layout.jsx):

hr.p: If you need to customize <ClerkProvider>, you can pass props like publishableKey, etc.

p.strong: Make sure you don't call Clerk hooks/components outside this wrapper

hr.p: Anywhere in your app, if you call useSession(), useUser(), currentUser(), or render <SignIn />, it must be inside a component rendered under <ClerkProvider>.

li.p: If you’re using Next.js middleware or API routes, those don’t need <ClerkProvider>, only React components do.
If you use currentUser() in server components, that’s different; but client hooks like useSession need client and <ClerkProvider>.

To fix this, try replacing alignment-baseline="middle" with dominant-baseline="middle" and adjust y a little. Also, sometimes dy helps fine-tune vertical position.

li.p: y="20" is exactly the circle center.
dominant-baseline="middle" better vertical align support.
dy="1" nudges the text down by 1 pixel to visually center it better.
